		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2012"></a><br><code>sle2012/paper21</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012</a> paper:</span><br><i>Approaches and Tools for Implementing Type Systems in Xtext</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/LorenzoBettini.html">Lorenzo Bettini</a>, <a href="../profile/DietmarStoll.html">Dietmar Stoll</a>, <a href="../profile/MarkusVölter.html">Markus Völter</a>, <a href="../profile/SeranoColameo.html">Serano Colameo</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_22">10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_22</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagM">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> The paper is about defining and implementing type systems (type calculation/conformance) for Xtext-based DSLs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It compares approaches within and around the Xtext language workbench, focusing on tool support and integration.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> Usability (required effort, flexibility, and developer experience) is an explicit comparison criterion for the surveyed approaches.
</li></ul></li></ul>
